        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1977-06-30T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1977-06-30T00:00:00-05:00" n="36"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d36">
                <head>36. Memorandum From the Assistant Secretary of the Treasury for International
                    Affairs (<persName corresp="#p_BCF_1">Bergsten</persName>) to Secretary of the
                    Treasury <persName corresp="#p_BWM_1">Blumenthal</persName>
                    <note n="1" type="source" xml:id="d36fn1">Source: National Archives, RG 56,
                        Records of Assistant Secretary of the Treasury for International Affairs
                            <persName corresp="#p_BCF_1">C. Fred Bergsten</persName>, 1977–1979, Box
                        1, FT-9 Manufactured Products 1977. Confidential; Nodis. Reviewed by
                            <persName corresp="#p_HC_1">Hessler</persName> and the Executive
                        Secretariat on July 1. Copies were sent to <persName corresp="#p_SAM_1"
                            >Solomon</persName> and <persName corresp="#p_BD_1">Brill</persName>. A
                        typed notation at the top of the page reads: “Noted by W.M.B.”</note>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>Washington</placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian"
                            when="1977-06-30">June 30, 1977</date>
                    </dateline>
                </opener>
                <list type="subject">
                    <head>SUBJECT</head>
                    <item>Steel Industry’s Request for Import Quotas</item>
                </list>
                <p>The presidents of 8 steel companies lunched with <persName corresp="#p_SRS_1">Bob
                        Strauss</persName> today, and laid on the table their specific proposals for
                    resolving their complaint under Section 301 of the Trade Act.<note n="2"
                        xml:id="d36fn2">No memorandum of conversation of this meeting was found, but
                        see <ref target="#d51">Document 51</ref>. Regarding the steel industry’s
                        case, see <ref target="#d30">Document 30</ref> and <ref target="#d30fn7"
                            >footnote 7</ref> thereto.</note>
                </p>
                <p>Their primary demand was for immediate imposition of import quotas against all
                    major and minor suppliers. Specifically, they want to roll back Japanese sales
                    from the current level of 8 million tons per year to 5 million tons.</p>
                <p>The industries claimed that 3 steel firms will fail in the absence of such
                    action. As far as I am aware, there was no discussion of pricing policy.</p>
            </div>
